&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;इस प्रकार सही उत्तर &lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;option 4&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt; है।&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is:&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;inventing&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Concocting&lt;/strong&gt; means to devise or create a plan or a story.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ex.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;The drink was first &lt;strong&gt;concocted &lt;/strong&gt;by a bartender in New York.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Inventing&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;means to create or design something.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ex.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;The Council is actually &lt;strong&gt;inventing &lt;/strong&gt;the wheel.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So, it is evident that&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;inventing&lt;/strong&gt; is closest in meaning to &lt;strong&gt;concocting.&lt;strong&gt;​&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is:&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;inventing.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Imagine &lt;/strong&gt;means&amp;nbsp;to suppose, assume or form a mental image of something.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Tell&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;means to communicate any information to someone else.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Own&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;means to have the possession or control of something.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;meta charset=&quot;UTF-8&quot;&gt;&lt;meta name=&quot;viewport&quot; content=&quot;width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0&quot;&gt;
&lt;title&gt;&lt;/title&gt;
&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The indirect speech sentence indicates that Thomas Muller expressed joy at Germany&amp;#39;s victory.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Option 3 correctly converts it to direct speech with the proper exclamatory phrase &amp;quot;Hurrah!&amp;quot; and the present perfect tense &amp;quot;has won.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Other options do not capture the exclamation or the specific wording accurately.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 3: Thomas Muller exclaimed, &amp;ldquo;Hurrah! Germany has won the tournament!&amp;rdquo;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 1:&lt;/strong&gt; While this option uses the present perfect tense &amp;quot;has won,&amp;quot; it lacks the joyful exclamation indicated in the indirect speech.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 2:&lt;/strong&gt; This option uses &amp;quot;won&amp;quot; in the past simple tense and an informal exclamation &amp;quot;Wow!&amp;quot; which is not as fitting as &amp;quot;Hurrah!&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 4:&lt;/strong&gt; This option uses the past simple tense &amp;quot;won&amp;quot; and lacks any exclamation indicating joy.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &amp;lsquo;&lt;strong&gt;Have you been ever&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The error is in the phrase &amp;lsquo;&lt;strong&gt;Have you been ever&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct phrase should be &amp;lsquo;&lt;strong&gt;Have you ever been&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;rsquo;, which correctly places &amp;lsquo;&lt;strong&gt;ever&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;rsquo; before the verb &amp;lsquo;&lt;strong&gt;been&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Hence, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&amp;lsquo;&lt;strong&gt;Have you been ever&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;​Therefore, the correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Option 2&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Correct&amp;nbsp;Sen&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;tence&lt;/strong&gt;: &amp;ldquo;&lt;em&gt;Madhu said to her friend, &amp;lsquo;&lt;strong&gt;Have you ever been&lt;/strong&gt; to a big city like Mumbai?&lt;/em&gt;&amp;rsquo;&amp;rdquo;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;lsquo;&lt;strong&gt;Madhu said to her friend&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;rsquo; is grammatically correct as it properly uses the verb &amp;lsquo;said&amp;rsquo; to indicate direct speech.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;lsquo;&lt;strong&gt;To a big city&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;rsquo; is also correct as it provides the object for the verb &amp;lsquo;been&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;lsquo;&lt;strong&gt;Like Mumbai&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;rsquo; is a correct use of a simile to provide an example of a big city. It correctly follows the phrase &amp;lsquo;to a big city&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;A very mild punishment.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The most appropriate meaning of the given idiom &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;A slap on the wrist&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;A very mild punishment.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;option 3&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;is a correct option.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Let&amp;#39;s discuss about&amp;nbsp;idioms:&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;​A group of words established by usage as having a meaning not deducible from those of the individual words.​​
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For example:-&amp;nbsp;
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;On cloud nine&lt;/strong&gt; -&amp;nbsp;Being very happy.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Get your act together&lt;/strong&gt; -&amp;nbsp;Get organized and do things effectively.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Back against the wall &lt;/strong&gt;-&amp;nbsp;Stuck in a difficult circumstance with no escape.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 2&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The primary issue in the sentence is the incorrect use of the article &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;A&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; before the term &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Himalayas&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The term &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Himalayas&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is a proper noun and should not be preceded by the article &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;A&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct phrase should be &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;The Himalayas stretch across&lt;/strong&gt;,&amp;quot; ensuring grammatical correctness and clarity.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Thus, the error is located in &lt;strong&gt;Option 2&lt;/strong&gt; of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 2&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;The Himalayas stretch across&lt;/strong&gt; the north-east part of India and pass through many countries.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;of one other&amp;quot;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error in the sentence is in the phrase &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;of one other&amp;quot;. &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct phrase should be &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;of each other&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;when referring to mutual support or actions between two or more parties.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Each other&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;is used when two entities are involved, and &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;one another&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;is traditionally used for more than two, but the sentence indicates a general situation implying two or more people supporting each other during crises, hence &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;each other&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;or &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;one another&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;could fit, but not &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;one other&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error changes the meaning of the sentence by making it grammatically incorrect and causing confusion about the intended message of mutual support.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The corrected sentence would read: &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;We must take care of each other in times of crisis.&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;ensuring clarity and correctness in conveying the importance of mutual support during difficult times.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Option 4&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;We must - This segment sets the tone for imperative or strong advice, suggesting an action that needs to be taken.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is grammatically correct.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;take care - This phrase is correctly used in this context to imply looking after or supporting one another.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It stands as a common expression for showing concern and kindness.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;in times of crisis - Refers to periods of difficulty or emergency.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This segment correctly indicates when the action of taking care of one another is especially emphasized.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

